snippet.textDisplay: Nice Gravlax I'm sure it's lovely.  Now, if you want to make the swedish dish with the same name, here is how you do it. Choose a nice side of Salmon. You might want to trim the end off it, to make it more homogenous in thickness. Cut the piece of salmon in two equally sized pieces. Now, salmon has a beatuiful natural color, you dont really need to dye it with Beetroot (jamie Oliver) or turmeric (Brad). This is a simple recipe, with clear simple flavors. Just mix 2 tbsp salt and 2 tbsp sugar. Add a lot of crushed WHITE pepper. rub it all over the meaty side. If you want a firmer skin, rub it over  the skin side. Put some nice big twigs of fresh dillweed over the meaty side of one piece of the salmon. Put the other piece, meaty side down, over it. Place in a container just slightly larger than the salmon, preferably non metallic. put a small plate over the salmon to distribute the weight. Put a weight on the plate, a jar of pickles or whatever comes in handy. Refrigerate for 36 to 48 hours, flip the salmon about halftway. If theres a lot of liquid when you turn it, get rid of some, but leave a little. Done. Slice it thinly. Try this sometime, because it really doesnt need gin, beetroot, bayleaf, garlic, curry or any of the other spins international chefs try to put on it. We eat it with a cold sweet mustard sauce, fresh dill and some potatoes.
